</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Calculus-Made-Easy-Silvanus-Thompson/dp/0312185480" target="_self">“Calculus Made Easy” by Silvanus P. Thompson</a> is more textbook-like than the other books in this list, but for a good reason. Thompson’s “Calculus Made Easy” is a painless introduction to calculus, and boils down the essence of calculus into something that is surprisingly approachable, even if you haven’t gotten into pre-calculus or trigonometry yet.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><mark>The first chapter is aptly titled, “To Deliver You From the Preliminary Terrors.”</mark> Without having taken a calculus course, one may be afraid of the complexities and abstraction that lay ahead. However, Thompson casts away all of those fears and explains calculus in a way that is simple and exciting.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I remember when I first picked this book up. I sat on a bench next to a small lake, and by page eleven I was smiling ear to ear. <mark>“I am understanding calculus,” I thought to myself! When I first purchased this book, I was in the middle of a semester in College Algebra (a prerequisite before trigonometry, and eventually, calculus).</mark> It made me feel confident and eager to continue my math education.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you’re slightly confused about what calculus is, or are awaiting your first calculus class, then this book is the perfect choice to introduce the topic.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
